    <string name="about_description_text">From japanese terms \'keitai\' (mobile) and \'jisho\' (dictionary). KEITAI JISHO is a project, driven by George Shazkho, which objective is to be a simple and useful tool for non-native japanese speakers. It has been built natively on Java (using Android Studio IDE and Android SDK tools), and it\'s based on some open source projects:</string>
    <string name="about_description_text_html"><![CDATA[
        <html>
            <head>
                <meta charset="utf-8"/>
                <style type="text/css">
                    body {
                      margin-left:      0;
                      margin-right:     0;
                      padding-left:     0;
                      padding-right:    0;
                    }
                    a:link, a:visited, a:hover, a:active {
                      text-decoration:  none;
                      color:            #8c1c1c;
                    }
                    li {
                      margin-bottom:    10px;
                    }
                </style>
            </head>
            <body style="text-align:justify">
                <strong>携帯 (keitai):</strong> Mobile (handheld)<br>
                <strong>辞書 (jisho):</strong> Dictionary<br><br>
                Keitai Jisho (mobile dictionary) is a free to use project, driven by George Shazkho, which objective is to be a simple and useful tool for non-native japanese speakers.<br>
                It has been built natively on Java (using Android Studio IDE and Android SDK tools), and it\'s based on some open source projects:
                <ul>
                    <li><a href="https://code.google.com/p/svg-android-2/">svg-android-2</a>: Open source library (Apache 2.0 liense). Used to display SVG images (kanji stroke order).</li>
                    <li><a href="http://www.edrdg.org/jmdict/edict.html">EDICT</a>: Free to use dictionary (Creative Commons v3.0). Used as the main dictionary on this app (term-based search).</li>
                    <li><a href="http://www.csse.monash.edu.au/~jwb/kanjidic.html">KANJIDICT</a>: Free to use dictionary (Creative Commons v3.0). Used as the kanji-specific dictionary (kanji-based search).</li>
                    <li><a href="http://kanjivg.tagaini.net/">KanjiVG</a>: Free to use collection (Creative Commons v3.0). Used as source for stroke order in kanji-based search.</li>
                    <li>WanaKanaJava: Java helper class. Partially implemented, helps translating inro Romaji. MIT licensed.</li>
                </ul>
            </body>
        </html>]]>
    </string>
